# Vendored JavaScript.
#
# There is no package.json and no build step: these four files are committed as
# they are served. This file is what makes that reviewable — without it an
# upgrade is an opaque binary diff, and a tampered bundle is indistinguishable
# from a legitimate one.
#
# Every version below was established by fetching the upstream artefact and
# comparing hashes, not by reading a version string out of the bundle. Two of
# the four carry no version marker at all.
#
# The sha384 values are also the SRI hashes in web/templates/page.html, and CI
# recomputes them from the files. Changing a bundle without updating both fails
# the build.
#
# To upgrade one:
#   1. curl -sSL <source> -o <file>
#   2. openssl dgst -sha384 -binary <file> | openssl base64 -A
#   3. update the hash here and the integrity= in web/templates/page.html
#   4. go build ./...   (the assets are go:embed'd; a rebuild is required)
#   5. check it in a browser — see CONTRIBUTING.md. A bad integrity value is not
#      a build error: the browser silently refuses to run the script.
#
# The files it describes live in static/files/js/vendor/. This file is here,
# outside that tree, because everything under files/ is go:embed'd and served —
# a manifest in there would ship to every user at /js/vendor/VERSIONS.
#
# format: <file> <package>@<version> <source> <sha384>

htmx.min.js
    htmx.org@2.0.10
    https://unpkg.com/htmx.org@2.0.10/dist/htmx.min.js
    sha384-H5SrcfygHmAuTDZphMHqBJLc3FhssKjG7w/CeCpFReSfwBWDTKpkzPP8c+cLsK+V
    verified: byte-identical to upstream

alpine.min.js
    @alpinejs/csp@3.15.0   — the CSP build, not the standard one
    https://unpkg.com/@alpinejs/csp@3.15.0/dist/cdn.min.js
    sha384-/RME6pSq0zKJyBifgNWPb3I8kZckbbyQzvFaUqSyfcw3anF1SmYxV5XUPlkZxTBZ
    verified: byte-identical to upstream.

    THE BUILD MATTERS. The standard alpinejs build compiles attribute
    expressions with the AsyncFunction constructor, which needs
    script-src 'unsafe-eval'. This one ships a tokenizer, parser and AST
    interpreter instead and installs it with setEvaluator, so no eval happens
    and the app's CSP can omit 'unsafe-eval' entirely.

    It is ~15 KB larger for that reason. Swapping back to the standard build
    silently reintroduces the eval requirement: nothing fails at build time —
    every binding simply stops working in the browser, because the CSP refuses
    the constructor.

    What it accepts: identifiers, literals, member and call expressions, binary
    and unary operators, conditionals, assignments, updates, array and object
    literals. What it does NOT accept: statements and sequences. `if (x) y()`
    and `a; b` are parse errors, which is why torrentRow exists in ct.js — one
    click handler had both.

